[[Image:Koto-in Zen Temple Kyoto - entrance walkway.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Entrance to K<U+014D>t<U+014D>-in, a sub-temple of [[Daitoku-ji]]]]

{{nihongo|'''K<U+014D>t<U+014D>-in'''|<U+9AD8><U+6850><U+9662>}} is a sub-temple of [[Daitoku-ji]], [[Kyoto]], [[Japan]]. It was founded by [[Hosokawa Tadaoki]]. There is a [[Chashitsu|teahouse]], the Sh<U+014D>k<U+014D>-ken, and the gardens are celebrated for their [[momiji]].<ref>{{cite book |title=A Guide to the Gardens of Kyoto |author1=Treib, Marc |author2=Herman, Rob |publisher=[[Kodansha]] |year=2003 |page=63 |ISBN=4-7700-2953-5}}</ref> A pair of [[Song Dynasty#Southern Song, 1127<U+2013>1279|Southern Song]] monochrome [[hanging scrolls]] with landscape have been designated a [[National Treasures of Japan|National Treasure]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bunka.go.jp/bsys/maindetails.asp?register_id=201&item_id=59 |title=Database of Registered National Cultural Properties |publisher=[[Agency for Cultural Affairs]] |accessdate=7 April 2011}}</ref> Many other works are aired annually in October.<ref>{{cite book |title=Daitokuji: The Visual Cultures of a Zen Monastery |author=Levine, Gregory P.A. |publisher=[[University of Washington Press]] |year=2005 |page=255 |ISBN=0-295-98540-2}}</ref>

